{
  "text": "In the present study, the decrease in growing follicles at P65 corresponded to a decrease in circulating serum AMH levels. In humans and rodents, AMH is present from the primary to the early Downloaded from https://academic.oup.com/biolreprod/article-abstract/98/5/664/4813326 by OUP site access user on 08 October 2018 antral stage [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , where it serves to inhibit primordial follicle recruitment from the ovarian reserve, and decrease FSH sensitivity of growing follicles [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Several studies have shown a strong correlation between antral follicle numbers and serum AMH concentrations, where high numbers of antral follicles are associated with high serum AMH concentrations [CITATION_5] . Since serum AMH levels decrease with age coinciding with an age-related antral follicle loss [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , AMH has been used as an indirect measure of the ovarian reserve in humans [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . In our study, a reduction in circulating AMH in UN offspring coincides with our observed reduction in antral follicle number, which would release the brake on primordial follicle recruitment thus potentially depleting primordial follicles in UN offspring [CITATION_10] . Although in the present study we show a very modest reduction in primordial number in young adult UN offspring, in previous work we showed that by 120 days of age UN offspring have decreased primordial follicle numbers [CITATION_11] . It appears likely, therefore, that these changes are driven by a reduction in AMH levels.",
